@chapter Overview
@cindex greetings
@cindex overview

The GNU @code{stools} program produces a familiar, friendly greeting.
It allows nonprogrammers to use a classic computer science tool which
would otherwise be unavailable to them.  Because it is protected by the
GNU General Public License, users are free to share and change it.

GNU @code{stools} was written by Juergen Schoenwaelder.

@node Sample, Invoking stools, Overview, Top
@chapter Sample Output
@cindex sample

Here are some realistic examples of running @code{stools}.

This is the output of the command @samp{stools}:

@example
hello, world!
@end example

This is the output of the command @samp{stools --help}:

@example
nothing
Usage: stools [options]
  -h, --help                    Print a summary of the options
  -V, --version                 Print the version number
@end example

@node Invoking stools, Problems, Sample, Top
@chapter Invoking @code{stools}
@cindex invoking
@cindex version
@cindex options
@cindex usage
@cindex help
@cindex getting help

The format for running the @code{stools} program is:

@example
stools @var{option} @dots{}
@end example

@code{stools} supports the following options:

@table @samp
@item --help
@itemx -h
Print an informative help message describing the options and then exit.

@item --version
@itemx -v
Print the version number of @code{stools} on the standard error output
and then exit.
@end table

